    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I like that <code>List.range</code> is just a normal function. <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"676210\">@Brian Teague</span> do you have a use case where the verbosity of <code>List.range</code> is bothersome?</p>",
        "id": 422973469,
        "sender_full_name": "Anton",
        "timestamp": 1708678609
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I personally use ranges a lot with Rust, and multiple languages support a similar syntax, so I wanted to ask if other people would also like it for fewer keystrokes.</p>\n<p>Haskell uses list comprehension for step</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Haskell\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">-</span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"o\">..=-</span><span class=\"mi\">8</span><span class=\"p\">]</span>\n<span class=\"p\">[</span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">3</span><span class=\"o\">..&lt;</span><span class=\"mi\">10</span><span class=\"p\">]</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 423058737,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Teague",
        "timestamp": 1708708117
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe it's because I rarely use ranges, but when I do, I often have to look up the syntax. So, I like how explicit <code>List.range</code> currently is.</p>",
        "id": 423060119,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1708708636
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That’s perfectly fine.  I just wanted to see if there was any demand for the shorthand syntax as I like it and use it a lot when available.  If no one else wants it, that’s perfectly okay too.</p>",
        "id": 423061261,
        "sender_full_name": "Brian Teague",
        "timestamp": 1708709002
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Sure! I'm not really opposed to it if there's demand, I'm just not part of the demand <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 423062105,
        "sender_full_name": "Agus Zubiaga",
        "timestamp": 1708709241
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wonder how much it would be used. In my mind, it is really common to use this type of syntax in <code>for</code> loops in <code>rust</code>. Roc doesn't have for loops and instead has tail recursion. Theoretically, one could use <code>List.range |&gt; List.walk</code> to create an equivalent loop (and long term hopefully it would optimize away the intermediate list), but I almost never write that. I write the tail recursive version.</p>\n<p>So at least from my current use of roc, I am pretty neutral. I guess I just have explicit indices in tail recursive loops most of the time. Is this a general FP difference or just a coding style...not actually sure.</p>",
        "id": 423087474,
        "sender_full_name": "Brendan Hansknecht",
        "timestamp": 1708719187
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't use ranges that often, so I prefer having only 1 way to it. But I think this is something that could be added to the language later on as well, if we see there is demand for it.</p>",
        "id": 423170541,
        "sender_full_name": "Norbert Hajagos",
        "timestamp": 1708781831
    }
]